# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-300
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The **1925 24 Hours of Le Mans** was the 3rd Grand Prix of Endurance, and took place on 20 and 21 June 1925.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was the last of the three races spanning 1923 to 1925 to determine the winner of the Rudge-Whitworth Triennial Cup, as well the second race of the inaugural Biennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO) was pleased with how the 1924 regulations had worked.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] They adjusted the hood-test so that all cars could do it at the same time.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The start was the logical point and to stop drivers from jumping the gun they would be lined up on the opposite side of the track.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] When the flag fell, they would run across, put the hood up and then start the car and get away as quick as possible.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] This became the origin of the famous “Le Mans start” that was an institution of the race until 1969, when safety concerns led to its end.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The ACO offered a FF500 prize for the quickest to put up their hood, and the French agent for Truffault-Hartford suspension parts offered a FF1000 prize to the car leading after the first lap.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The hoods now had to stay up for at least the first twenty laps (about two hours), and they had to be examined by officials for robustness before being pulled down.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] In addition to the 20-lap rule between fluid replenishment, no liquids could now be added after 3pm, in the final hour of the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Another important change was that every car had to cross the finish line and take the chequered flag to be classified.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Using the cars’ average race speeds, the officials would calculate each car's estimated position on the track at the 24-hour mark.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The sliding scale of target distances were again adjusted, though not as severely as 1924.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year there were a number of cash prizes awarded by the ACO and assorted sponsors for events ranging from leading at certain times to quietest and most comfortable cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Finally, this race was the culmination of the inaugural Triennial and Biennial Cups.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Only seven manufacturers' entries remained who had completed both the 1923 and 1924 races to be in contention for the Triennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] There were eight entrants for the Biennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Both would be decided solely by the results in this race, not from the combined aggregate.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] With the further success of the race, the ACO looked at getting more permanent facilities.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] They tried to purchase the properties around the pit area at *Les Raineries* however the prices demanded by the landowners were too high.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Frustrated, the ACO instead resolved to relocate with more amenable neighbours by the hippodrome along *Les Hunaudières*, the main route from Le Mans to Tours.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] A new temporary pits, lighting and grandstands were set up on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The national roads board assisted by widening and sealing the track around the new pits area to assist with the new start procedure.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The international attention that had come with Bentley's win the previous year drew a much bigger list of entries.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Of the 68 submitted, 55 arrived for scrutineering.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] But this included 15 cars from outside France.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Sunbeam, AC and Austin joined Bentley from Great Britain, and there were teams from Italy (Diatto and OM) and the USA (Chrysler).
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] There were also six different tyre companies represented at the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] After their distance victory the previous year, Bentley returned with a full works car to support John Duff’s privateer entry and carrying the “favourites” tag.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The works car had an uprated 3.3-litre engine and was driven by Bentley salesman Bertie Kensington-Moir and Dudley Benjafield, a Harley St doctor and Bentley racer at Brooklands.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Chenard-Walcker were well-placed in both Rudge-Whitworth Cups and arrived with four cars split over two engine-sizes to hedge their bets.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The plan was to chase the Cups with the smaller cars and go for the distance victory with the bigger ones.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Once again, their lead drivers René Léonard and André Lagache were assigned their primary car – the latest version of the 22CV.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] This was lower and now had a straight-8, 3.95-litre engine.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The second car was driven by 1924 team hero André Pisart, and Jacques ‘Elgy’ Ledure, formerly with Bignan.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The smaller cars were inspired by the streamlined Bugatti Type 32 ‘tank’.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Designer Henri Toutée's advanced Z1 was a racing version of the upcoming Y8 tourer.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] It had a new 1.1-litre engine produced 50 bhp and had new steering and 4-wheel braking, making it very quick.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] They were assigned to Sénéchal/Loqueheux and Glaszmann/de Zúñiga.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] After coming very close to victory the previous year, La Lorraine-Dietrich arrived with three of their B3-6 cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The cars had been lightened, and the troublesome steel “artillery” wheels were replaced by Rudge-Whitworth wire ones.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] All three cars were now on Englebert tyres.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Last year's driver pairings were shuffled a bit: Gérard de Courcelles and André Rossignol stayed together, but Brisson was with Stalter and Robert Bloch with the new Léon Saint-Paul.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Sunbeam were now ready for Le Mans and arrived with two cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Founded in 1899, the company came to pre-war prominence with French designer Louis Coatalen.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Making aero-engines for Bristol during the war, they had been forced to merge with Talbot-Darracq in 1920, becoming STD.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Already with a strong racing pedigree, with Land Speed Records for Kenelm Lee Guinness and Malcolm Campbell, they became the only British carmaker to win a Grand Prix in the first half of the twentieth century when Sir Henry Segrave won the 1923 French Grand Prix.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Coatalen developed the two cars for Le Mans from the current production 24/60 model.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The 2.9-litre engine put out 90 bhp with a 4-speed gearbox.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] With 4-wheel braking, they also ran with Rapson tyres like the Bentleys.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Segrave was perhaps the most well-known British racing driver, and was paired with George Duller, while the second car had works drivers Jean Chassagne and *Autocar* journalist Sammy Davis.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Originally a British company, Talbot had been bought out by the British-owned, Paris-based Darracq company 1919, which then merged with Sunbeam the next year.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Its production was relocated to Paris and it was two of the 1.5-litre Type C, first made in 1923, that were sent to Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ariès brought a newmodel to Le Mans this year.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Type S GP2 was lowered, with a shorter wheelbase and an improved 3-litre engine.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year company-owner *Baron* Charles Petiet was able to procure the services of the great Louis Wagner who had raced Darracq, FIAT and Mercedes before the war, and recently with the Alfa Romeo works team.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ariès also bought a pair of its smaller CC2 1100cc cars to compete for the 1924-5 Biennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The biggest car in the field was a Sizaire-Berwick, in the Anglo-French company's only Le Mans appearance.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Designed by Maurice Sizaire in Paris, the cars had originally been made in London.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Financial struggles saw that factory bought by Herbert Austin who put his own engines in the cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The model at Le Mans had been built in France, its 4.5-litre engine putting out 65 bhp.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although big, it was also heavy and its performance lagged behind the new racing tourers.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year cars came from Italy for the first time, with two Italian teams.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Diatto was an old industrial firm and had built railway-stock in the 19th century, including carriages for the famous Orient Express.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] It branched into cars in 1905 and had a solid pre-war racing pedigree.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The works team was now run by Alfieri and Ernesto Maserati and four cars came to Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Tipo 35 had a 3-litre engine putting out 75 bhp and capable of 135 kp/h (85 mph), while the pair of Tipo 30s had 55 bhp 2-litre engine.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Officine Meccaniche (OM) was a Milanese company that likewise building was founded, in 1899, building railway wagons.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The 665 “Superba” had come out five years later.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] It had a 2-litre engine, 4-speed gearbox and 4-wheel brakes.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The model S was a short-wheelbase, racing version with Pirelli tyres and an improved engine that put out 60 bhp capable of over 120 kp/h (75 mph); and it had performed well at the national level.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Three cars came to Le Mans with Italian drivers including Grand Prix drivers “Nando” Minoia and Giulio Foresti.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was also the first race for an American team.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The first Chrysler-badged car had only been unveiled in 1924.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Chrysler Six Model B-70 had a 3.3-litre straight-6 engine that produced 70 bhp capable of over 110 kp/h (70 mph).
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Dwarfed by the production of Ford and General Motors in the US, Chrysler set out to outset its rivals in Europe.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The French agent was Gustave Baehr's Grand Garage Saint-Didier in Paris, and it was they who entered two cars into the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the end there was only time to prepare one – for former Lorraine-Dietrich driver Henri Stoffel and Lucien Desvaux, ex-Salmson.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The other new British team to enter was AC Cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Originally making a 3-wheel delivery vehicle called an Auto Carrier, it was the post-war investment by famous British racer Selwyn Edge, that got the new AC Six into production.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The entry was raced by John Joyce and Victor Bruce (engaged to famous female racer Mary Petre).
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Louis Reval had been in the automotive industry since the turn of the century.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] His company, Automobiles Reval, was only three years old.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The latest iteration of his Type A had a 2.5-litre engine with a short-wheelbase Sports chassis and could reach 120 kp/h (75 mph).
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Automobiles Gendron (also known as GM) was originally an auto-parts manufacturer, but started making cars in 1922.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Two of the long-wheelbase GC-2 1.5-litre tourers were entered.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Company founder Marcel Gendron himself drove one car, with accomplished aircraft test-pilot Lucien Bossoutrot.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Similarly, Henri Précloux was new to car-manufacturing, having opened E.H.P. in 1921, making small-engined cars and cyclecars that were competitive racers.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The D4 model was new for 1925, and the DT was a higher-specification variant with a 1.5-litre CIME engine and 4-speed gearbox.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Rolland-Pilain had released two new models this year: the B25 road-car and a “Super Sport” version of the B23, and it was three of the latter that were at Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] It had a longer wheelbase, “boat-tail” rear end and a more powerful 2-litre engine.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The cars of Delalande/Chalamel and de Marguenet/Sire were entered in the Triennial Cup and with two cars, the team had a good chance in the Triennial field of seven.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Bignan were struggling financially and only sent a pair of their 2-litre cars, to contest both of the ongoing Cups.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The distinctive cars now sported on a single large headlight in the top of the radiator grill.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] SARA again had three entries, and this year bought along a pair of its new Type BDE.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Still with the 32 bhp 1100cc engine, they could now get up to 100 kp/h (60 mph).
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Amilcar arrived with a works-entry CGS this year, to compete for the Triennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Team drivers were André Morel and Marius Mestivier.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] However, this year they were not the smallest car in the field.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Eric Gordon England, former Bristol test pilot, entered a 748cc Austin Seven.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Built with his own patented ash and plywood bodywork design weighing only 9kg.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year, the ACO was able to get the public roads closed to allow teams to do practice laps on the Friday – between 5am -8am and then 9pm-midnight.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Earlier, in private practice, Léonard's Chenard-Walcker collided with a lorry coming away from the Pontlieue hairpin but was not badly damaged.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Sunbeams developed issues and were sent to the Talbot sister-factory in Paris for repair, returning in time for the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] André Guilbert, a mechanic for Reval, was testing one of the cars when he hit a delivery van head-on when exiting the Pontlieue hairpin.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] He was taken to hospital with critical leg injuries.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] On Saturday morning Oméga-Six company owner Gabriel Daubech withdrew his three cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Team driver Jacques Margueritte had trialled two of the cars and picked up significant engine issues.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was a hot, sunny weekend for the race and over twice as many spectators as the previous year arrived for the event.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Once again it was Émile Coquille, co-organiser and representative of the sponsor Rudge-Whitworth who was honorary starter.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Just as the cars were forming up on the grid, the AC team found their radiator mounting was cracked, and with insufficient time to do a repair had to withdraw.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] John Duff won the FF500 prize for being the first to put his hood up on his Bentley and get away, followed by the big Sizaire-Berwick and Kensington-Moir in the other Bentley.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] But at the end of the first lap it was Segrave in the Sunbeam in the lead, chased by the Bentleys, Saint-Paul's Lorraine and the two large Chenard-Walckers.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] On only the fourth lap, Pisart bought his Chenard in leaking water and overheating from a ruptured water-hose.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] After 40 minutes of repairs, they struggled on for two more laps but there was no way they could get to twenty for the next water refill.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] In a similar predicament was the little Austin Seven, which got a stone thrown through the radiator after only nine laps.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] With the new track surface, the drag of the hoods being up and fast race-pace several teams had miscalculated their fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Kensington-Moir had just passed Segrave for the lead when the Bentley ran dry on his 20th lap near Pontlieue.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] But he got back to the pits and illegally secreted a bottle of petrol back to the car to get it back to the pits, but losing seven laps.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] René Léonard was the first to pit, on the 20th lap, and Lagache was cheered away by the, naturally, parochial French spectators.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] He set about lowering his own lap record by 9 seconds.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Then at dusk a serious accident occurred, The Amilcar of Marius Mestivier was just about to be overtaken by André Pisart's Chenard-Walcker just after the new finish-line approaching the Mulsanne corner.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] It suddenly slewed sideways off the track and rolled.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Mestivier was crushed and killed instantly – the first fatality at the endurance race.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Pisart made it round to the pits and retired the next lap with a ruptured water-hose causing overheating.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] At 9pm the Segrave/Duller Sunbeam retired with a broken clutch, while the sister car had been delayed by a sticking throttle.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] As night fell Davis, in avoiding a backmarker, dropped the other Sunbeam off the road into a ditch.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Despite a bent rear axle, he got back to the pits where the team inspected the car and resolved to carry on.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Just after midnight the suspension on Léon Saint-Paul's Lorraine broke at speed, throwing the car into three spins before rolling.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Badly injured, Saint-Paul was pulled from the wreck by Tulio Vesprini (currently running 5th) who sportingly stopped his Diatto to help and then stayed with the driver until an ambulance arrived.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Sénéchal finally handed over his 1100 to Loqueheux at midnight after driving solid for 8 hours.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Both cars already looked to have a strong grip on their respective Cups.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Sénéchal was back in his car at 2am when he went off the road and over the ditch in the fog at Arnage.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Fashioning a bridge from some fencing, while lit by nearby spectators, he managed to get the car back onto the road and carried on in less than an hour.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Like the little Chenard-Walckers, the 2-litre Bignans had also been running exceptionally well, running third and fourth at 10pm – with the Springuel/Clause car possibly getting up to second overall going into Sunday, until both were delayed and lost time.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] As dawn approached by the halfway point at 4am the Lorraine of Rossignol/de Courcelles had done 65 laps, holding a 2-lap lead over their teammates Brisson/Stalter.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The recovering Sunbeam was third a further lap back and the Leduc/Auclair Talbot in fourth.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the next fuel stops, the Bentley's engine caught fire.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Despite Clement dowsing it with his seat-cushion, the damage was too severe to carry on.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The remaining 4-litre Chenard retired when it too overheated from a ruptured water-hose and facing 8 laps until it could be replenished.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The sister cars were brought in for precautionary checks and had their hoses replaced.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Sunbeam finally caught and passed Brisson for second place around 6am.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] By breakfast time, the Lorraines were split by the Sunbeam with two of the Italian OM's running very well in fourth and fifth.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] As with the previous year, the Rolland-Pilains were compromised by their low fuel economy and could never push to their full potential.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although their lead car (of de Marguenat/Sire) was running well, in the top-10, the other two were delayed.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Chrysler had been having a strong reliable run that had got it up to 7th on distance.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Then with less than two hours to go, Stoffel ended up in a ditch avoiding a slower car.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The delay was crucial because, despite driving hard to make up lost time, they finished just two laps short of their qualifying distance.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Meanwhile, the leading cars continued without further incident to the finish.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the end Rossignol and de Courcelles finished laps ahead of the opposition and ten laps ahead of their target.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Chassagne and Davis in their Sunbeam held on to second, just ahead of the other Lorraine, of Brisson/Stalter.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The two OMs came home in fourth and fifth staging a formation finish.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Danieli brothers were just ahead of teammates Foresti / Vassaux in a strong display of reliability from the newcomer team.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The streamlined Chenard-Walcker 1100s ran like clockwork.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Glaszmann/de Zúñiga car finished 10th overall winning the inaugural Biennial Cup, while Sénéchal/Loqueheux came in 13th overall to win the first, and only, Rudge-Whitworth Triennial Cup (Sénéchal drove for over 20 hours).
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The cars were also sitting first and second respectively at the halfway point of the next Biennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although only one of the three Rolland-Pilains finished, it was as runner-up in the Triennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The team was also awarded one of the special cash prizes this year: FF500 for being judged one of the three most comfortable cars, a prize shared with the Ravel.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Sadly Ravel's mechanic, André Guilbert, died in hospital on the Tuesday following from his injuries.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Small consolation for the Chrysler team for missing entry to the Biennial Cup was getting the FF500 prize for having the quietest car.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The two 3-litre Diattos had also been having a strong race.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] So it was tough when the Lecot/Renaud car had to retire with less than two hours to go.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Rubbietti and Vesprini had been pushing hard making up for the time spent by Vesprini tending the injured Saint-Paul.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] However, the grateful Lorraine-Dietrich team donated them FF1000, with a further FF1000 given by the Hartford company and Saint-Paul's teammate Édouard Brisson.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] At the time they were France's third-biggest car manufacturer, assisted by their endurance racing successes.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] The top pairing of Lagache/Léonard won the second Spa 24-hours three weeks later (and were third the year after).
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] However, the team never returned to Le Mans, the works team was disbanded at the end of 1926 and the company faded into obscurity.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] A number of companies were now starting to suffer in the saturated car-market as more high-volume production-line cars filled the streets.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Lucien Rolland and Émile Pilain were forced by their board to sell their shares and their factory moved from Tours to Paris.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] In 1926, E.H.P. bought out Bignan and Majola was taken over by Georges Irat.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] And after the Italian government defaulted on its repayments for vehicles to Diatto, it was forced to dissolve its racing team at the end of the year.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Results taken from Quentin Spurring's book, officially licensed by the ACO Although there were no official engine classes, the highest finishers in unofficial categories aligned with the Index targets are in **Bold** text.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] There were no official class divisions for this race and these are the highest finishers in unofficial categories (used in subsequent years) related to the Index targets.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Archived from the original on 11 September 2018.
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] *"Le Mans 24 Hours 1925 - Racing Sports Cars".
[src:chrysler-300/1925-24-hours-of-le-mans] Archived from the original on 5 July 2017.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The **1952 24 Hours of Le Mans** was the 20th Grand Prix of Endurance, and took place on 14–15 June 1952 at Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] After 22 years away, Mercedes-Benz returned in triumph, scoring a 1–2 victory with their new gull-wing Mercedes-Benz W194 which was equipped with a 3.0L S6 engine that had less power than the road car sold two years later.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Aston Martin, with their DB3, joined Ferrari, Jaguar, Mercedes-Benz, and Cunningham in the top-level sports prototype game, setting the stage for the rivalries that provided so much drama during the rest of the decade.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This race was notable in that Pierre Levegh attempted to drive the entire 24 Hours by himself.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] With just over an hour to go however, a connecting rod in the engine of Levegh's car broke, taking it out of the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO) decreed that mudguards now had to be integral with the bodywork, unlike the pre-war style of cycle-type mudguards.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This meant cars had proper sports-car bodies and were not just modified Grand Prix cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] After ongoing issues with the fuel used in the race, the ACO's ‘ternary' fuel was made up of 75% petrol, 15% alcohol and 10% benzole.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The minimum replenishment period for fuel, water and oil was extended from 25 laps to 28.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The target average lap speeds (i.e. minimum distances per hour) for each class were also increased.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Finally, after 19 runs of the event, the prize money (FF 1 500 000) for the race-winner was raised to make it the same as that for the Index of Performance winner – just reflecting the stature that the teams and spectators had always placed on the overall race win.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] There were over a dozen multi-car works teams that year, along with self-built team owners and works-supported private entries.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] There were less than 20 genuine private entries, well in the minority of the 60 starters and reserves.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year the big news was the return of Mercedes-Benz and Rudolf Caracciola to La Sarthe after 22 years, and the first entry from the Scuderia Ferrari works team.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Mercedes, led again by their pre-war team manager Alfred Neubauer, arrived with a trio of Mercedes-Benz W194 sportscars named '300SL' *(Sport Leicht)*, which would lead to the road-going fuel-injected 1954 Mercedes-Benz W198 *Gullwing* of the same name.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] To fit into a low racer, the 3.0L S6 engine of a new limousine was tilted at a 50° angle, and race-tuned as Mercedes-Benz M194 engine, still fitted with carburettors.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The cars had tubular frames with high sides, and in the first two races, Mille Miglia and supporting the 1952 Swiss Grand Prix, had only small *gullwing windows* above the closed sides.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] These were considered too small by the ACO organizers, thus new chassis had to be made, with doors that cut half way into the sides.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Mercedes also tested tilted air brakes above the roof, these were not allowed to race.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The cars had run for over 12 hour at the Mille Miglia, and were tuned down a fraction to 165 bhp for better 24 hour durability.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Along with Neubauer was only one of three pre-war Mercedes team drivers, Hermann Lang.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Rudolf Caracciola was entered on the No.22T car, but in May had broken his leg in Switzerland, and this ended his illustrious career.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Even worse happened to Luigi Fagioli who had won the 1935 Monaco Grand Prix for Mercedes, but got injured before the recent 1952 Monaco Grand Prix sports car race, and would die after the Le Mans race.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Karl Kling was the other post-war team leader, with a third car given to lesser known drivers.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Jaguar returned with a strong 3-car team.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Having been beaten for speed by the new Ferrari and Mercedes-Benz in the Mille Miglia, the C-types were hurriedly redesigned with a more aerodynamic shell, which unfortunately meant a smaller radiator and a relocated header tank.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] They also presented a strong driver line-up with the previous year's winners Peter Walker with Stirling Moss, and Peter Whitehead with new driver Ian Stewart, as well as Tony Rolt and Duncan Hamilton who had previously driven for Healey.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Aston Martin, after their great success in the 1951 race, arrived with three new DB-3 cars, as well as two privately entered DB-2s, all fitted with the reliable 2.6L S6 engine.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Sydney Allard decided to change engines this year, swapping the Cadillac for a Chrysler V8 and the new J2X had new bodywork to comply with the new ACO regulations.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year Donald Healey entered a pair of Nash-engined prototypes, one with a new body for the British drivers, the other with a new engine for his French drivers.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Talbot was the last of the old French manufacturers remaining in the large-engine classes with four privately entered T-26 cars (with strong support from the factory), now with the required new enclosed bodywork.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] André Chambas had modified his 4.5L engine by adding twin-superchargers which (by using the x1.4 supercharge-equivalence factor) meant his car (#6) had the biggest effective engine capacity and started at the head of the grid.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Gordini, having gone their separate ways from Simca, were now powered with their own engines: a smaller team with the standard 1100cc car, and a special 2.3L version for its regular GP drivers, Jean Behra and Robert Manzon, which was very nimble.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] With the swarm of small-engined Panhards, Renaults and Simcas (as well as a supercharged Peugeot special), the French were the biggest nationality represented with 20 cars, followed by the 18 British cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ferrari was back again in force, with eight entrants including two in a works team, and a trio from Luigi Chinetti's American team.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The '250 S' was to be driven by Enzo Ferrari's GP drivers Alberto Ascari and Luigi Villoresi, while the smaller works '225 S' was driven by Tom Cole Jr., latterly with Allard.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Even Louis Rosier had jumped from Talbot to a pair of Ferrari 340 Americas.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] He was entered in one (racing with fellow French F1 racer Maurice Trintignant) and the other for his son.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Lancia's first foray the year before had been a win, and the works team returned with a pair of updated B20 Aurelias to again contest the 2-litre class.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Another pre-war veteran, Luigi Fagioli, was to have driven (after scoring a 3rd place in the Mille Miglia) but had been critically injured at the same Monaco GP that Ferrari had won and could not compete.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Another future Italian stalwart of the race made its debut this year: OSCA had been set up by the three Maserati brothers after selling their namesake company, and arrived with their first sports car, the MT-4.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Its 1.3L engine developed 90 bhp, putting it in a competitive contest against the Jowetts and Porsche.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Briggs Cunningham returned with his own cars and regular team-drivers John Fitch and Phil Walters.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year they had two new C-4R roadsters and one with a closed coupé body (C-4RK) designed by renowned pre-war aerodynamicist Wunibald Kamm.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Made over 500 kg lighter than the 1951 C-2, they claimed the biggest engines just ahead of the Allards, with the burly 5.4L Chrysler 'Firepower' V8 putting out 320 bhp.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Potential works entries from Alfa Romeo (for Juan-Manuel Fangio and José Froilán González) and Pegaso were scratched amid concerns about the cars being able to last the distance.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The remodelled Jaguars soon showed up overheating problems what were to plague them through the race, despite some hasty modifications.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] A Le Mans star of the future, Phil Hill drove one of the Cunninghams in practice, but not in the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the second practice session, Griffith heavily crashed his Aston Martin into the sandbank at Tertre Rouge, but team manager John Wyer managed to swap in the spare car without the officials noticing.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Also needing a full rebuild after a practice crash was the new DB coupé.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] A piston failure during practice forced the scratching one of Louis Rosier's Ferraris.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] But it was Hermann Lang in the Mercedes which both set the fastest unofficial top speed on the 3 mile Mulsanne Straight, at some 150 mph.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] And the fastest lap in practice at 4m40s, just a tenth ahead of Ascari's Ferrari, with both fully 20 seconds faster than the ‘official' time of the Cunningham in 1951.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] After the wet race the previous year, this year's race was essentially dry.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Leader after the first lap was Phil Walters in the Cunningham coupé, chased by Moss in the Jaguar and the red and blue Ferraris of Ascari and Simon respectively, then the other two Jaguars and "Levegh's" Talbot.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ascari soon got to the front and between him and Simon they took turnabout lowering Stirling Moss's lap record – eventually setting it six seconds faster than the previous year.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Soon enough though, after just 6 laps, Ascari was in the pits with clutch problems – something that would plague the Ferraris through the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Moss had moved back up to second when Ascari pitted but soon was also pitting, with overheating problems.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] By nightfall all three Jaguars were out of the race in a dramatic change of fortune to the previous year.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Two of the Aston Martins had retired with differential issues.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Phil Walters had kept the Cunningham coupé in close reach, and after 4 hours handed the car over to his co-driver Duane Carter who promptly planted it into the sandbank at Tertre Rouge on his second lap out.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Soon after getting back in the race their engine started playing up with similar problems that had already sidelined John Fitch's car.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Surprising the home crowd, that moved the Gordini of Robert Manzon up behind Simon.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Though running a much smaller engine than the cars around it, it was proving very fast.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] When Simon had to start nursing a slipping clutch, Manzon took the lead in the 3rd hour.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Meanwhile, the three Mercedes-Benzes were playing a waiting game, running to Neubauer's strict, conservative pace to preserve the cars and hovering just in the top 10.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] After several trips to the pits, Vincent stuck the former lead Ferrari into the sandbank at Mulsanne corner, dropping it right down the order.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Chinetti's own Ferrari moved up into the top five, while his 3rd car had fallen to clutch problems in the early evening, as had Rosier's car.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Going into the night, Manzon and Behra kept their lead, and by midnight were a lap ahead of "Levegh" in his Talbot.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] However just before half-time one of the Gordini's brakedrums jammed and despite repairs the team considered too dangerous to risk continuing.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This left "Levegh" sitting four laps ahead of the two Mercedes-Benzes of Helfrich / Niedermeyer and Lang / Riess, followed by the Macklin / Collins Aston Martin.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] But it was not an easy lead – he had already decided to drive right through on his own; the engine had developed a vibration and he did not want to risk his co-driver, René Marchand, with a breakdown.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] As in 1930, the leading Mercedes (Kling/Klenk) had retired during the night with a broken alternator, but this time it was backed up by two other Mercedes.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Luigi Chinetti's Ferrari had been disqualified for refuelling a lap ahead of its prescribed time, leaving just the Simon / Vincent Ferrari in the race gradually making back ground.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] After successive second places in the previous years, luck ran out for Mairesse / Meyrat when their (aging) Talbot's oil pump expired around half-time.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Dawn was masked by a heavy fog, which got so thick the Mercedes drivers had to open their gull-wing doors to be able to see.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] It also caused Alexis Constantin to crash and roll his supercharged Peugeot at Tertre Rouge barely missing Jack Fairman's Allard.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The other Allard had an equally hairy moment soon after when Arkus-Duntov found himself with no brakes at the end of the Mulsanne straight taking to the escape road, scattering spectators and *gendarmes* and narrowly avoiding parked cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] As the sun rose, Neubauer instructed his drivers to finally pick up the pace, but it was too late, the lead was too great.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] "Levegh" had driven through the night and still held a good lead.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Near noon a damaged wheel cost Helfrich time and dropped his car to third.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Macklin and Collins kept their Aston Martin at a steady pace in fourth.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Late in the morning the leading Frazer-Nash of "Dickie" Stoop / Peter Wilson broke a halfshaft and retired, leaving the Lancias comfortably in front.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Also retired at this time was the larger-engined Porsche, leading the S1500 class in a close tussle with the OSCA, running 14th and 15th overall respectively.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] It had come in to refuel and left the engine running in case it stalled permanently.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] That was against the safety rules and the officials disqualified the car.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] But the OSCA was no more fortunate: soon afterward, just coming out of Arnage, the clutch broke.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Lacour got out and pushed the car the 3 km back to the pits only to be told by his pitcrew that the damage was terminal.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The race was quietly running down to its conclusion, with the home crowd looking forward to a second French victory in four years.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] But then suddenly, with just over an hour to go, the connecting rod of "Levegh's" Talbot broke, causing it to come to a halt at Maison Blanche about a mile from the pits.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Driving without a working rev-counter, it is uncertain whether either the engine issues finally broke it, or through sheer exhaustion, he missed a gear-change and over-revved the engine catastrophically.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] But such was his lead it still took 20 minutes for the second-placed Mercedes-Benz to get ahead on distance.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] A final twist saw the Aston Martin retire, moving the Nash-Healey of Johnson/Wisdom up to 3rd ahead of Briggs Cunningham's own car and the recovering Ferrari of Simon / Vincent.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Like many, Cunningham had been nursing a slipping clutch through most of the race, driving for 20 hours himself gradually moving up the order.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] So Mercedes-Benz, using undersized underpowered engines, were as surprised as anyone to have the 1-2 victory.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This was the first win for a closed-body car, and for a German manufacturer.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although the weather had been good, it was a torrid race with a record 40 retirements from the 57 starters.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The lone Ferrari had fought back into the top ten during the morning, and after the late-race retirements made it up to 5th.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The privateer team of Clark and Keen was the only Aston Martin to finish this year (in 5th) and the only Talbot to finish was Chambas' supercharged special in 9th.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] For the third year in a row, Pierre Hémard won the Index of Performance (although this year his co-driver was Eugène Dossous) in the little Monopole-Panhard. just ahead of the two Mercedes-Benz coupés.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] They also won the Biennial Cup and romped home in their S750 class fully 13 laps ahead of the closest Renault.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Jowett also won its class, the S1500, for the third successive year, by outlasting the much faster but more fragile opposition.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Lancias barely missed a beat getting a successive class win.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Porsche repeated its S1100 class victory from the previous year, and by the same drivers as 1951: Paris Porsche agent, ‘Toto' Veuillet and Edmond Mouche.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] The last finisher in the race was a little Renault 4CV driven by Le Mans debutante, Jean Rédélé who, at 30 years old, was France's youngest Renault dealer.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] After a short racing career he would go on to found a significant new car company with Renault rear-mounted engines: Alpine.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] A varied field of cars led to a competitive race.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] This helped cement Le Mans' place as one of the most important race on the motorsport calendar.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Mercedes-Benz went on to win the Nürburgring and in the Carrera Panamericana.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] These races, along with Sebring 12 Hours, Mille Miglia and Le Mans, were run again next year as part of the inaugural 1953 World Sportscar Championship.
[src:chrysler-300/1952-24-hours-of-le-mans] Gordini had its biggest success two weeks after Le Mans in Formula 2, when Jean Behra beat the Ferrari 500s in the final Grand Prix de la Marne at Reims.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] The **3rd Grand Prix, 12 Hours of Sebring**, was the inaugural round of the 1953 World Sportscar Championship and was held at the Sebring International Raceway, on 8 March 1953.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] A total of 81 cars were entered for the event, across eight classes based on engine sizes, ranging from up to 750cc to over 8.0 litre.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] Of these 59 cars practised, 54 qualified to race.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] Amongst the mostly American entrants, the greatest news for the 1953 race was that the famous English Aston Martin team would join the French factory DB’s for the 12 Hour competition.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] In fact, David Brown and René Bonnet, heads of these European manufacturers, both went to Florida to watch the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] The race started at noon, and ran until midnight, on a day described as "partly cloudy and mild", in front of an estimated crowd of 12,500 spectators.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] The Aston Martins made a great start, leading the first 32 laps of the Florida road course before losing the lead as a result of an accident.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] The #57 Cunningham C-4R then took over lead and was never headed for the rest of the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] The car was driven by Phil Walters and John Fitch took the winner spoils for Briggs Cunningham’s team.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] They were boosted to the lead when the front running Aston Martin of Geoff Duke and Peter Collins collided with a Jaguar, and was forced to retire with accident damage.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] Walters and Fitch drove their Florida license plated Cunningham C-4R to victory, covering a distance of 908.9 miles, averaging a speed of 75.338mph.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] There was one car fire, the Allard-Cadillac J2X of Paul Ramos was destroyed when a fuel line split, however the driver, Anthony Cumming escaped unharmed.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] Another competitor, Randy Pearsall, also escaped injury when he flipped his Jaguar XK120.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] Championship points were awarded for the first six places in each race in the order of 8-6-4-3-2-1.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] Manufacturers were only awarded points for their highest finishing car with no points awarded for positions filled by additional cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] Only the best 4 results out of the 7 races could be retained by each manufacturer.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-12-hours-of-sebring] Points earned but not counted towards the championship totals are listed within brackets in the above table.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The **1953 24 Hours of Le Mans** was the 21st Grand Prix of Endurance, and took place on 13 and 14 June 1953, at the Circuit de la Sarthe, Le Mans (France).
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was also the third round of the F.I.A.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] British drivers Tony Rolt and Duncan Hamilton won the race with one of three factory-entered Jaguar C-Types, the first cars ever to race at Le Mans with disc brakes.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] With the ongoing success of the World Championship of Drivers, this year saw the introduction by the FIA of a World Championship for Sports Cars, creating interest from the major sports car manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] It also drew together the endurance races in Europe and North America.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Le Mans race was the third round in the championship after the 12 Hours of Sebring and the Mille Miglia.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year also marked the first use of a radar-‘gun’ to measure speeds across a flying kilometre on the Hunaudières Straight.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Cunningham would touch almost 156mph.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Some 6 mph faster than last years winning Mercedes gull wing coupe.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The prestige of the race, as well as the advent of the new championship, generated interest in Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Of the 69 entrants and reserves, nineteen different marques (and their subsidiaries) were present.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] 56 works-entered cars were officially represented, with over half in the main S-8000, S-5000 and S-3000 classes.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Mercedes-Benz did not return to defend their title – they were busy preparing new cars for both the F1 and Sports Car championships.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] So the overall victory was shaping up as a contest between Italy (Scuderia Ferrari, S.P.A.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Alfa Romeo and Scuderia Lancia), England (Jaguar supported by Aston Martin, Allard and Nash-Healey/Austin-Healey and the United States (Cunningham), with the French (Talbot and Gordini) being the ‘dark horses’.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Drivers included all three F1 World Champions to date (Alberto Ascari, Juan Manuel Fangio, Giuseppe Farina) and over 30 other current and up-and-coming Grand Prix racers.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Italian teams had built new cars for the season and all had strong driver line-ups.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ferrari entered two lightweight Ferrari 340 MM Berlinettas powered by the company's big 280 bhp 4.1 litre V12 engine built for a challenge at Mille Miglia.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ascari and Luigi Villoresi were to share another lightweight coupé 375 MM converted to 4.5-litres, while brothers Paolo and Gianni Marzotto (winner of the 2nd round of the championship: the Mille Miglia) and Giuseppe Farina and debutante Mike Hawthorn were down to drive the 340 MMs.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] A third 340 MM Spyder was entered by American Ferrari agent Luigi Chinetti for himself, with Anglo-American Tom Cole (who had finished 3rd with Allard in 1950) as his co-driver.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Such was the quality of the entry list that six other Ferraris could not make the starting list.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Alfa Romeo was back at Le Mans for the first time since the war and fielded the beautiful new 6C/3000CM (‘’Cortemaggiore’’) powered by a 3.5L S6 engine (developing 270 bhp and 245 km/h) for Fangio and Onofre Marimón and Consalvo Sanesi and Piero Carini.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The third car was driven by Mercedes-Benz works-drivers Karl Kling and Fritz Riess who also had their team manager, Alfred Neubauer, in the pits with them.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Lancia this year stepped up to the big class with three new D.20 Coupés.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Having just won the non-Championship Targa Florio with a 3.0L V6 engine, team manager Vittorio Jano instead decided to install supercharged 2.7L engines.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] This proved to be a mistake as the small increase in power (to 240 bhp) increased unreliability and gave away over 20 km/h top speed to the rival Jaguars and Ferraris.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] GP-racers Louis Chiron and Robert Manzon, Piero Taruffi and Umberto Maglioli were in the team, with José Froilán González and endurance-race specialist Clemente Biondetti in the reserve car.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Jaguar returned with their C-Types and after the debacle of the previous year, were determined not to repeat those mistakes, having undertaken a lot of development work.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Team manager ‘Lofty’ England employed the same driver pairings as 1952, with Peter Walker and Stirling Moss, Peter Whitehead and Ian Stewart, and Tony Rolt and Duncan Hamilton.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The cars reverted to the aerodynamic design prior to that of the 1952 Le Mans cars, whose revised nose and tail had adversely affected stability at speeds over 120 mph.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] For 1953 the cars were lighter and more powerful (now developing 218 bhp), and they were the first-ever Le Mans cars equipped with disc brakes, from Dunlop, whose greater efficiency gave the C-Types a distinct advantage over their drum-braked competitors.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The disc brakes had been available in 1952, but given the problems with the radiators they had been swapped out so the team could concentrate on just one potential issue in the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The works cars were supported by a standard production-body car entered by the new Belgian Ecurie Francorchamps team.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Aston Martin entered their new DB3S cars for Reg Parnell and Peter Collins, George Abecassis and Roy Salvadori, and Eric Thompson and Dennis Poore.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Using the same 3-litre engine as the DB3, it was put into a newly designed, shortened, chassis.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] However it was suffering from considerable lack of testing, being well down on speed.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Donald Healey this year had two collaborations: his last year with Nash Motors with a pair of long-tailed models, and a new partnership with the Austin Motor Company using its 2.7L engine, producing only 100 bhp but capable of 190 km/h.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Bristol also arrived with two cars for Lance Macklin / Graham Whitehead and Jack Fairman / Tommy Wisdom, and managed by former Bentley Boy and Le Mans winner Sammy Davis.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The rear-engined 450 coupés were ugly and noisy but the 2 litre engine could get them to nearly 230 km/h.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year Talbot entered a full works-team, rather than just providing support to privateer entries.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The trio of blue T26 GS cars were driven by Talbot regulars Guy Mairesse (with Georges Grignard), Louis Rosier and Elie Bayol, and Pierre Levegh and Charles Pozzi.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although still very fast, they were starting to show their age to the nimbler cars from Italy and Great Britain.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] André Chambas also returned with his supercharged modified SS spyder for a 5th and final time.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Gordini had intended to debut the new 3.0L T24S, but scratched it because of atrocious handling.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Instead an uprated T16 design, the T26S with a 2.5L engine was prepared for Maurice Trintignant and Harry Schell.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] An older T15S was entered for Behra and Mieres.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Though it only had a 2.3L engine it was lighter, and just as quick as its bigger brother.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Without Mercedes-Benz, German representation fell to works teams from Borgward (here for the first and only time) and Porsche, both in the medium S-1500 class.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Porsche stepped up from the S-1100 class with a new, purpose-designed race car, the 550 Coupé and its flat-four 1488cc engine, making only 78 bhp but a top speed of nearly 200 km/h.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] There were also a pair of the smaller 356 SL in the S-1100 class.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] As expected the French dominated the smaller-engined classes.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The most eye-catching were the four from Panhard, bringing cars with their own badge this time under a new competition department, albeit under close collaboration with Monopole: with very aerodynamic designs from French aviation engineer Marcel Riffard using both of the Panhard engines.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Other works entries came from Renault, DB and Monopole themselves.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] In Thursday practice the Jaguars showed their class with all three works cars going under the lap record, but drama also happened when the 3rd car, of Rolt and Hamilton, was disqualified.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] It had been on track at the same time as another Jaguar which had the same racing number (the spare car being used as a precaution to qualify Norman Dewis, the Jaguar test driver, as a reserve), and a protest raised by the Ferrari team.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Jaguar chairman, Sir William Lyon, agreed to pay the ACO fine, and ‘Lofty’ England successfully pleaded his case to the official that no intention to cheat had been meant and it was an honest mistake and so they were reinstated.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] But Hamilton's account of the affair has become motor racing legend.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Devastated by their disqualification, he and Rolt had gone into the city for the night to drown their sorrows, and when England found them at 10am the next day (race-day) at Gruber's restaurant, they were nursing hangovers and drinking copious amounts of coffee.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] England later said: "Of course I would never have let them race under the influence.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] I had enough trouble when they were sober!" Tony Rolt also said the story was fiction.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Spanish Pegaso team withdrew both their entries after Juan Jover crashed his Z-102 Spyder during practice.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Misjudging the speed of his approach to the corner after the Dunlop bridge, he hit the barriers at over 200 km/h and was thrown from the car, seriously injuring his left leg.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] With no apparent explanation for the crash, the team decided on safety first and scratched the other car.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was the first and last time they got to Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] At 4:00pm on the Saturday, the flag fell and the race was on.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] As usual, Moss was quick out of the blocks and led the cars away, but the Allard passed him on the Mulsanne straight and was leading the closely bunched field at the end of the first lap.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] But Sydney Allard’s early lead barely lasted, and by lap four he had to retire with a collapsed rear suspension that severed a brake pipe.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The first few laps at Le Mans mean little and it was not until after 30 minutes that the true nature of the race became apparent.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Rolt had already put in a lap record at 96.48 mph, while Moss led the way, closely followed by Villoresi, Cole, Rolt, Fitch, with Karl Kling rounding out the top six.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although he had pulled away from the chasing pack, a misfire had set in after only 20 laps, in the second hour.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The unscheduled pitstop to change spark plugs, plus another later for the eventual fix – removal of a clogged fuel filter – dropped the car down to 21st.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] At least Jaguar had remembered the pit regulations: A Ferrari mechanic topped up the brake system on Mike Hawthorn’s 340 MM before the specified 28 laps had been completed, thereby Hawthorn/Farina were disqualified.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Whilst all this was going on, Villoresi had taken the lead.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] By 5pm, at the end of the first hour, the order had settled down and it became clear that the Jaguars, Ferraris and Alfa Romeos were the teams to be reckoned with.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Lancias and Talbots were quite outclassed, as were the medium-engined Aston Martins.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The race continued at a fantastic pace and now it was Jaguar setting it: passing Villoresi, Rolt lifted his lap times by 5 seconds to push his lead.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Then Consalvo Sanesi, in his Alfa Romeo 6C, continued to lower the lap record.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Just before 6:00pm, Fangio retired with engine troubles in his Alfa Romeo.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] At the three-hour mark, Rolt/Hamilton led from Ascari/Villoresi, followed by Cole and his co-driver Luigi Chinetti, Sanesi/Carini, and the Germans Kling and Riess.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Already these five cars had pull out a two lap advantage over the rest of the field.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] As darkness fell, the Ferrari-Jaguar battle continued unabated, between Ascari/Villoresi and Rolt/Hamilton, with the Alfa Romeos close behind and the overall order swapping around according to pit-strategy.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] During the early hours of the morning, Rolt and Hamilton continued to lead, while the Ferrari was now losing ground – the big engine starting to stretch the rest of the powertrain.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Gordinis were once again punching above their weight, mixing it in the top-10 with the third works Jaguar, the other Ferraris and the Cunninghams.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The smaller-engined car was a high as 7th ahead of its stable-mate until its rear-axle seized, necessitating long repairs that proved terminal soon after midnight.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the other classes the Porsche 550s had the measure of all the smaller cars and, aside from those superfast Gordinis, were even running ahead of the S2.0 and S3.0 cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Just after midnight, Tommy Wisdom's Bristol had an engine fire (almost an identical problem had hit its sister-car earlier in the evening).
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Crashing, Wisdom was trapped for a short while before being rescued and taken to hospital with minor burns and a dislocated shoulder.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Then just before 3am, the rear suspension on the Sanesi/Carini Alfa Romeo had collapsed, and they were out, along with George Abecassis and Roy Salvadori with oil getting into their Aston Martin's clutch.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although the Ascari and Villoresi car was still taking the fight to the Jaguars, the car was hindered by a sticking clutch and drinking a lot of water.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] However, the Italians, in a win-or-bust attempt, were driving flat out at all times, but it had no effect on Rolt and Hamilton.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Their Jaguar now had a lap lead over the Ferrari.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Despite the night being clear and fine, dawn approached with a certain amount of mist in the air, making driving conditions very tiring.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Just after 6.30am Tom Cole, running 7th, had just overtaken a back-marker when he lost control at the Maison Blanche corners.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Ferrari ploughed into the roadside ditch then rolled and struck a wooden hut nearby.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Cole was hurled out of the car in the initial impact and died at the scene.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The windscreen on the leading Jaguar had been smashed early in the race by bird-strike, and as result Rolt and Hamilton were suffering from wind buffering, but the pair kept up the pace nevertheless, with an average speed of well over 105 mph.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] By the time the mist had cleared, Rolt and Hamilton still led by a lap from the struggling Ferrari.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Third place, over three laps adrift, was the Cunningham of Fitch/Walters and a lap further back were the fast Jaguars of Moss/Walker (back in the race after a terrific hard drive back through the field) and Whitehead/Stewart.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Shortly after 8:30am, the leading Jaguar and Ferrari both made routine refuelling stops at the same time.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Hamilton had what would now be termed an “unsafe release” when, in the rush to beat the Ferrari, he pulled out right in front of one of the DB-Panhards coming in for its own pitstop.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Walters had a big moment when his Cunningham blew a tyre at high speed but he was able to catch it.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] But with the subsequent pitstop to fix the damage, Moss was able to move up to third.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] By 9:00am, the clutch issues with the lead Ferrari gave it a long stop, and it was now back in fifth place.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] This left Rolt and Hamilton clear up front, but they could not rest as Fitch and Walters started to fight back and hound the Moss/Walker Jaguar for second place.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The lame Ferrari retired just before 11am having dropped down the order to sixth place.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] This left only the Marzotto car to challenge the Jaguars and the lead Cunningham.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] It could not do it and raced to finish in fifth, keeping the Gordini of Maurice Trintignant and Harry Schell behind them.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Lancias had never made an impression, none having made it into the top-10 and just after midday the engine of the last one running (of González and Biondetti) gave up.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] With three hours to ago, the Jaguars were still lapping at over 105 mph, however the pace had slackened a little.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the closing stages the order did not change, as Hamilton took over from Rolt to complete the last stage of the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Driving their British license-plated Jaguar C-Type they took the victory, covering a distance of 2,555.04 miles (4,088.064 km), doing 304 laps and averaging a speed of 106.46 mph (170.336 km/h).
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Moss and Walker were four laps adrift at the finish, in second place with their C-Type after their epic drive.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The podium was completed by Walters and Fitch, in their Cunningham C-5R a lap back.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The third works Jaguar finished fourth, two laps further behind the Americans, after a very conservative and reliable race.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Marzotto brothers brought home the sole remaining Ferrari in fifth, finishing with virtually no clutch but having stayed in the top 10 throughout the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] A lap back was the Gordini, having had a trouble-free run.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Owner-driver Briggs Cunningham came in 7th followed by the works Talbot of *Levegh*, finishing this year, and the private Jaguar, entered by Ecurie Francorchamps for Roger Laurent and Charles de Tornaco, in their standard C-Type.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] In a race of attrition where only 1 car, if any, of the many other works teams finished, it was an effort of reliability that all cars of the Jaguar, Cunningham and Panhard works teams finished.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Panhard team staged a formation finish, winning the Index of Performance by a narrow margin.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The DB-Panhards had a good run, with that of owner-driver René Bonnet winning the S-750 class ahead of its sister car, and finishing 5 laps clear of the OSCA, instead winning the bigger S-1100 class.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] They were on course for the Index of Performance win, but a bad engine misfire meant it used too much fuel on its very last lap.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] The streamlined Panhard won the Index by a small margin on a countback.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] This was the first time a car completed the race with an average speed over 100 mph (in fact the first six finishers did) and covered over 2500 miles (4000 km).
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] All the categories broke their class records, and a new lap record was set.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Following the race, Alfa Romeo withdrew from motor racing.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Jowett was already in receivership and it would also be the last Le Mans for Allard, Lancia and Nash-Healey.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Manufacturers were only awarded points for their highest finishing car, with no points awarded for positions filled by additional cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] *"Le Mans 1953: Jaguar's gigantic leap — History, Le Mans".
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Foreword by Earl Howe to "Touch Wood!" Archived 2009-02-28 at the Wayback Machine Retrieved on 3 August 2008.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Daily Telegraph obituary of Tony Rolt, 2 February 2008.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] Obituary of Tony Rolt by Alan Henry, 9 February 2008.
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] *"1953 Le Mans 24 Hours report — History, Le Mans".
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] *"1953 24 Hours of Le Mans Results and Competitors".
[src:chrysler-300/1953-24-hours-of-le-mans] "1953 24 Hours of Le Mans: Night of the Disc Brakes".
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The **1954 24 Hours of Le Mans** was a race for Sports Cars which took place on 12 and 13 June 1954, at the Circuit de la Sarthe, Le Mans, France.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was the 22nd 24 Hours of Le Mans and also the fourth race of the 1954 World Sportscar Championship.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The race was won by José Froilán González and Maurice Trintignant driving a Ferrari 375 Plus.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] People viewed this race as a battle between brute force and science (per the July 1954 "Motor Sport" article).
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the high technology corner, with its sleek, aerodynamic bodywork was the new 3.4-litre Jaguar D-Type, and in the other corner was Ferrari's formidable 5.0-litre V12 375 Plus.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The race was heavily affected by poor weather throughout and was a thriller right to the end, producing the closest finish for the race since 1933: less than 5km (half a lap).
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The ACO again extended the replenishment window (last updated in 1952) of fuel, oil and water from 28 to 30 laps (405 km) although brake fluid was now exempted from this restriction for safety reasons.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The equivalence multiplier for forced-induction engines (i.e. supercharged) was reduced from x2.0 to x1.4.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] On the track, the stretch from the corners at Mulsanne to Arnage was widened to 8 metres (finishing the work starting in 1950) and the Indianapolis corner was given a slightly banked camber.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] This was the first year the race was aired on TV, which brought more attention to the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] But there were still 85 cars registered for this event, of which a full field of 58 arrived for practice as the remaining manufacturers increased their presence.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] As before, Jaguar's sole racing focus for the year was Le Mans and after their 1953 success, they arrived with three of the new Jaguar D-Type - purpose-built for the smooth tarmac of La Sarthe.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Engineers had developed a single vertical wing design for the event after wind-tunnel testing.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] This in addition to the low ride height (only 32 inches (810 mm)) made the vehicle highly aerodynamic.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The cars were equipped with a 3.4-litre straight-6 engines redesigned and tilted at 8 degrees (to reduce height, like the Mercedes-Benz 300 SL had done) that developed 250 bhp, enabling a top speed of over 270 km/h.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The first chasis prototype, the XKC 401, was completed within 2 months of early Le Mans trials and notably performed the trial laps with an unpainted chasis.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The driver line-up was kept pretty much the same from 1953 with winners Tony Rolt / Duncan Hamilton, and 2nd place Stirling Moss / Peter Walker.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year Peter Whitehead was paired with F1 driver Ken Wharton (his former co-driver Ian Stewart was racing with his brother, Graham, at Aston Martin).
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] An ex-works C-Type was provided for the Belgian Ecurie Francorchamps team when their original car was crashed on the way to the circuit by a Jaguar mechanic.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Not as fast as the Jaguar, but its excellent acceleration was a suitable equaliser on a power-circuit such as Le Mans, with its long straights.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] With them were Paolo Marzotto (the only works finisher in the 1953 race), ex-Gordini driver Robert Manzon (like Trintignant) and Louis Rosier, 1952 race winner with Talbot.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] They were backed up three other Ferraris entered by Briggs Cunningham's and Luigi Chinetti's American teams.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Glamour came with Chinetti's team with film star Zsa Zsa Gabor accompanying her rich playboy-boyfriend, Dominican Porfirio Rubirosa.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Maserati had taken over the Formula 1 world in early 1954 with its outstanding 250F winning the first two races.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] They had also developed an uprated version of their A6GCS sportscar, replacing the 2.0-litre engine with the 2.5L version from the 250F.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] A standard 2.0-litre version was also privately entered, with factory support, for the Marquess of Portago.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] OSCA had started the year sensationally when a 1500cc MT-4 entered by Cunningham and driven by Stirling Moss and Bill Lloyd won the Sebring 12-hours against far more powerful opposition.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Always looking to be competitive, as well as running the Ferrari 375 MM (because Ferrari had refused to sell him an engine for his own cars), Cunningham had tried to secure the new Dunlop disc brakes for his cars.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] However Jaguar used its contract-right to veto the deal.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] He arrived with a pair of the older Cunningham C-4R roadsters for his regular driver complement– the sole entrants in the Over-5 litre class.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] It was a big entry for Lagonda-Aston Martin with five works cars and two private entries.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] One of the two DB3S spyders had a supercharged 2.9L engine that developed 235 bhp driven by British F1 drivers Reg Parnell and Roy Salvadori, the other was run by Carroll Shelby.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Alongside them were a pair of aerodynamic coupés & the long-running, expensive Lagonda sports car with a 4.5L V12 (effectively a double-Aston Martin engine) Gordini arrived with four cars, competing in three classes.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The lead car, a T24S driven by Behra and Simon, had a 3.0L engine developing 230 bhp and new Messier disc brakes was capable of over 230 km/h.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Gordini also entered a pair of older T15S, also with disc-brakes but with 2.5L and 2.0L engines respectively.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Talbot sent no works team this year but supplied an improved 4.5L engine (now capable of 280 bhp) for the T26 spyders of the three private entries (*Levegh*, Meyrat, Grignard).
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the S-2000 class Bristol returned with three coupés developed from the previous year's model, with better styling and improved aerodynamics.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] There were also three Frazer-Nashes, using the same Bristol engine, as well as the first entries in the race for Triumph (an off-the shop-floor TR2) and Maserati.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Porsche returned with three cars to contest the S-1500 category against the OSCAs.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Porsche 550s were given the new quad-cam Porsche 547 engine making 110 bhp and 210 km/h, and this year were open-top spyders.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Another was also given a smaller 1089cc engine for the S-1100 class.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The small British sportscar firm Kieft arrived with two cars to take on the smallest Porsche – bringing the first fibreglass chassis to Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] One was also the first car with the new Coventry Climax FWA engine.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The small-engine classes were well-represented, and again dominated by the French Renault and Panhard derivatives.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] This year DB had five cars present that comprised a pair of the tiny new central-seat HBR model with Panhard engines and three HDR models using rear-engined Renault power.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Panhard itself, now with a full racing department, had 4 works entries built by Monopole who also had their own entry.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Jaguar was able to get an unofficial practice in May on the full track in an unrelated event and Tony Rolt took the prototype D-type round fully 5 seconds faster than Alberto Ascari's lap record from the previous year in the Indy-engined Ferrari.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the official practice, all three works cars recorded identical times. and they and the Ferraris were a step up from the rest of the field.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Overall, the Jaguars had better handling, disc brakes and were faster (Moss was timed at 154.44 mph/278 km/h over the flying kilometre, giving a huge 20 km/h advantage), but the Ferrari had superior power and acceleration.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The supercharged Aston Martin, the Lagonda, and the Porsches were also impressively quick.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Unfortunately the Maserati works transporter broke down en route to the track and the car had to be withdrawn as it arrived too late for scrutineering.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Marquess of Portago was able to take the start however, as he had driven his own car direct from the Modena factory in Italy.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Controversially, Gilberte Thirion qualified the 2-litre works Gordini but was excluded from competing because of her gender (only three years after the *Coupe des Dames* was awarded to female drivers) – her father drove in her stead in the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] At 4pm the race was started under dark clouds by Prince Bernhard, consort of Queen Juliana of the Netherlands, and an avid motor-racing fan.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] It came as no surprise when the mighty 375's of González, Marzotto and Manzon stormed away in 1-2-3 formation at the start, with Moss, Rolt and Wharton (who had a startline collision) in close pursuit.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] After only five laps the first heavy downpour arrived, negating the Ferrari power advantage.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] By the end of the first hour, González and Marzotto and Moss had a gap over Rolt, and Manzon.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The rest of the field was already a lap down.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Forty minutes later on lap 22, still in heavy rain, Moss managed to take the lead, starting the to-and–fro battle between the two marques.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Wharton had been held up in the first hour with a blocked fuel filter and over the next couple of hours, the other two Jaguars suffered engine misfires giving the Ferraris a lap's lead over the field.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Walker stopped out on the track for 50 minutes, but the Moss/Walker car would not be staging an epic comeback this year.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Meanwhile, Behra's Gordini and Fitch's Cunningham were regularly trading places in the top-10, mimicking the disc-brakes versus power battle at the front.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] However soon after 7pm, Behra pitted with ignition problems and then stopped out on the track beyond Mason Blanche.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] He pushed the car all the way back to the pits to get going again, but it eventually retired in the middle of the night.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] A number of other cars had been caught out in the rain: On only lap 5 *Count* Baggio planted the playboy Ferrari right into the Tertre Rouge sandbank and could not dig it out (so Rubirosa never got a chance to drive for his movie-star girlfriend).
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The other American Ferrari, of Fitch/Walters, was running 6th when a rocker-arm broke, dropping them out of the running while the engine was repaired.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Eric Thompson spun the Lagonda backwards into the bank at the Esses.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] After nearly 2hours to get it mobile and back to the pits it was retired because the rear lights were too badly damaged and deemed unsafe.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] After four hours, at 8pm, González and Marzotto were lapping together, still having not swapped with their respective co-drivers, and a lap ahead of Rosier and Whitehead.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Salvadori was fifth in the supercharged Aston, then Hamilton and the two Aston coupés, the Belgian Jaguar and Cunningham's own car filling out the top ten.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] At 9.30pm, the Talbot of Meyrat collided with the Aston Martin of 'Jimmy' Stewart as both were lapping a slower car in the fast section coming up to Maison Blanche.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Meyrat ended in the hedgerows, but the Aston Martin rolled throwing Stewart clear.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The car was completely written off and Stewart was very lucky to only suffer a serious arm break (that eventually contributed to his retirement from racing).
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The mid-evening showers caused another flurry of accidents and retirements, including *Levegh* who was in 8th place when he spun and wrecked his Talbot's suspension.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] As the rain finally eased off Wharton and Whitehead made a strong comeback, getting back to 3rd which became 2nd when the Maglioli/Manzon Ferrari broke its gearbox just after 11pm.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The D-types were now steadily hauling themselves back into contention.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] At midnight González/Trintignant were two laps ahead of Whitehead/Wharton.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Manzon/Rosier were third, ahead of Rolt/Hamilton and the Aston Martins of Parnell/Salvadori and Collins/Bira completing the top six.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The rain returned and the lead Jaguar had to pit again with fuel-line issues.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] After several more pitstops it finally retired with a broken gearbox.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Third was the other Ferrari, followed by the Spear/Johnston Cunningham and the supercharged Aston Martin.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Just afterward, in an unusual co-incidence, *Prince* Bira crashed his Aston Martin, while running in 4th place, within yards of Thompson's Aston coupé that had crashed earlier.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the next hour, the Herrmann/Polensky Porsche, leading the S-1500 class and an impressive 7th place overall, retired with a blown head gasket.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] As dawn arrived the Ferrari of Rosier/Manzon, running third, retired with a broken gearbox, jammed in second gear.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Now the battle was reduced to just one car for each team at the front of the field.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The clouds built up and rain became an ever-present threat, which would be advantageous for the aerodynamic D-types.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] By breakfast time, the rain started to come down very heavily and the stage was set for a heroic chase.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] González and Trintignant could afford to take things cautiously, but any unnecessary delays would enable the pursuing Jaguar to open up a chink the Ferrari's armour, and as the rain intensified, the sole remaining D-type piled on the pressure.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] But Trintignant responded and both cars roared round doing sub-4'30" lap-times.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] By 9.30am, after González's fuel stop when the Ferrari hesitated in restarting, the Jaguar team got more motivation and the lead was down to 3 minutes.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] But at 10am, Rolt glanced the bank coming out of Arnage lapping a slower car, and 2 minutes were lost in the pits for a bout of impromptu panelbeating.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The rain then eased during the morning, allowing the Ferrari to use its power to better effect, but still the Jaguar would not give up.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Despite this, the race order remained fairly constant and at midday the order was still Ferrari, Jaguar, Cunningham, Jaguar, Cunningham, Aston Martin, Gordini and the OSCA as the leading small-engined car.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The two remaining Porsches were running slowly, trying to get to the end of the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The supercharged Aston Martin had been running surprisingly well all race until just after midday when a head-gasket failure caused its retirement.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Around 1pm a ferocious squall slowed all the cars to a snail's pace, then the Jaguar drivers began to close the gap again on Trintignant as the track dried.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] With just two hours left to run, González and Trintignant were still almost two laps ahead of the English car.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Ninety minutes to run and Trintignant brought the Ferrari in for a routine stop.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] González took over, but the V12 refused to restart.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Ferrari lost 7 minutes as the mechanics desperately worked on the engine.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The rain started again and Rolt was now in sight: he came in to stop for new goggles, but his pit crew waved him on, and now the Jaguar was on the same lap as the leader.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Finally the Ferrari mechanics found the problem: the rain had saturated the ignition wiring.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] When González finally got going he was now only 3'14" ahead of the Jaguar.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] With thunder and lightning now lashing the circuit and unable to see, Rolt pitted and handed over to Hamilton for the final assault with an hour to go.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Hamilton then put in extraordinary times in the rain, cutting the lead to just 90 seconds.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] González was exhausted (he had not eaten or slept through the weekend) and his lap times dropped to 5'30", but his pit-crew urged him on and as the rain stopped with a half-hour to go, and the track dried out, he was once more able to bring the power of the Ferrari to bear again and extend the gap.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Finally able to ease off on the final lap, González crossed the line to win by just under three minutes - but still the closest finish in the race since 1933.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Meanwhile, in the smaller classes, the pair of works OSCAs had an ample lead of 15 laps over the struggling Porsches and running in the top-10 overall.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Yet within ten minutes, with just 2 hours to go, everything fell apart.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] First, the leading one of Giardini crashed and rolled at Mulsanne, then the one running second hit the barriers at Dunlop curve.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Pierre Leygonie ran the short distance back to the pits to get equipment and advice from the pit-crew.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] He managed to get it going again and back to the pits to hand over to Lance Macklin but they were then disqualified at race-end for having abandoned the car.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] To round off a bitter race for OSCA, their last car was running second in the S-1100 class but its transmission broke in the final laps of the race.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Despite the atrocious weather, González and Trintignant had still driven their Ferrari 375 Plus through 302 laps, just 2 laps less than the year before, and covering over 2,500 miles (4,000 km).
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] In his delight, Prince Bernhard jumped aboard with Trintignant for his victory lap in the rain.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] In the end it came down to pit-time: 37 minutes for the Jaguar versus 29 minutes for the Ferrari.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The podium was completed by the American pair, William "Bill" Spear and Sherwood Johnston, in their Cunningham C-4R, who were far behind, 19 laps (over 250 km) back, Briggs himself came in 5th.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Despite their very reliable Chrysler engines, the Cunninghams were unable to match the pace of the leaders.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Splitting the two American cars was the Belgian Jaguar which had run like clockwork despite not getting any pre-race testing.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The last remaining Gordini came in 6th earning a special FF1 million prize as first French car home.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] After the demise of the OSCAs, Porsche inherited class wins in the S-1500, and S-1100, by having the only cars left running in their classes.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Bristol had a great race: finishing 6-7-8 overall and a clear 1-2-3 in their class.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Although running most of the race behind the smaller OSCA, their leader finished over 30 laps ahead of the only class-competitor Fraser-Nash to finish.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Aside from a window-wiper making life difficult for Wilson/Mayers (they had to drive at times with the door open to see out!) and Jack Fairman spinning with less than an hour to go (thereby losing the class win) they had a trouble-free run.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The little DB cars also had one of their best races – finally winning the Index of Performance, as well as the Biennial Cup.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Owner-driver René Bonnet and Élie Bayol finished a remarkable 10th overall with a class-distance record (going further than Nuvolari's winning Alfa Romeo 20 years earlier), embarrassing many far-bigger cars left in their wake.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Monopole entry was second in class, but had the remarkable record of having spent a mere five minutes and ten seconds at rest in the pits for the whole race.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] One who did not finish was the last Talbot running – after numerous issues with engine and gearbox problems, the pit crew sent it out with ten minutes to go to do the final lap, but it could not complete it within 30 minutes and so was not classified.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Argentinian winner earned a special place in Ferrari history: Three years earlier, he had scored Ferrari's first F1 victory.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Now, in his last appearance at La Sarthe, he also gave the first victory for the Scuderia Ferrari at Le Mans.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The weather had precluded any chance of breaking distance records, although in the dry both González and Marzotto had smashed Ascari's lap record by over 10 seconds.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Despite its abortive attempt in this race, the 2-litre Maserati proved dominant across Europe, winning over 20 class wins in the season.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] In October, DB inaugurated the first one-make race series, *Formula Monomill* for young drivers, using an 851cc DB-Panhard.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The first race, at Montlhéry, was won by Jo Schlesser.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The Porsche 550s had great success in the Championship's final round, in the Carrera Panamericana, with Herrmann finishing an excellent 3rd overall.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] The year before they had a class win, and the name 'Carrera' was applied to the 356 road-cars with the quad-cam engine.
[src:chrysler-300/1954-24-hours-of-le-mans] Many sales followed to privateer racers, furthering the company's racing reputation.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] This fourth-generation transmission by Mercedes-Benz replaced the older 4-speed 4G-Tronic transmission-family and its 5-speed derivative, and was replaced by the much more complex and costly 7-speed Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission (model **W7A 700** · type **722.9**) introduced in 2003.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] Due to its high torque capacity and lower cost, it was retained for turbocharged V8 and V12 engines, 4-cylinder applications and commercial vehicles for almost a decade.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] Production ended in 2020 with niche applications like Sprinter with petrol/CNG M111 engine and Jeep Wrangler.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] Activated by a toggle switch, Winter mode sets the gearbox to start off in 2nd gear, both in Drive and Reverse.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] This is designed to reduce wheelspin on icy surfaces.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] Also in "W" mode the transmission will shift at lower speeds.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] "S" mode is not sport but Sommer (German for summer) or Standard.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] With Jaguar XJR applications the switch is labeled "Sport." In regular driving mode the gearbox starts off in 2nd gear, both in Drive and Reverse, and will only engage 1st gear when triggered via the kickdown switch (Drive only).
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] While "Sport" mode is enabled the gearbox will always start off in 1st gear.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] Speedshift is a performance feature set for the Mercedes-Benz transmissions which includes manual mode and active downshifting.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] When cornering at high speed, the transmission maintains the same gear above a certain lateral acceleration level.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] It can also automatically downshift before overtaking.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] It was first used in 2001 Mercedes-Benz C 32 AMG and 2001 Mercedes-Benz SLK 32 AMG.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] A version with mechanical lock-up of the torque converter from first gear and steering-wheel-mounted shifter.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] AMG Speedshift is also used in 7G-Tronic transmission.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] It was first used in 2002 Mercedes-Benz E 55 AMG, S 55 AMG, C55, CL 55 AMG.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] A version used in Mercedes-Benz SLR McLaren.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] The **5G-Tronic** is an electronically shifted 5-speed overdrive automatic transmission with torque converter lock-up, typically in gears 3, 4 and 5.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] The main objective in replacing the predecessor model was to improve vehicle fuel economy with extra speeds and a wider gear span to allow the engine speed level to be lowered (downspeeding), which is a decisive factor in improving energy efficiency and thus reducing fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] In addition, the lower engine speed level improves the noise-vibration-harshness comfort and the exterior noise is reduced.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] The need of 2 housings and 2 different controls turn out the **W5A 030** as the least economically designed automatic transmission ever manufactured for passenger cars.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] This was only possible thanks to computer-aided design.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] The 5G-Tronic is the 1st generation in which in-line epicyclic gearing have been combined with parallel epicyclic gearing.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] The resulting progress is reflected in an even better ratio between the number of gears and the number of components used compared to all layouts previously used by Mercedes-Benz.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] That is why Mercedes-Benz refers to them as **NAG 1 (N**ew **A**utomatic Gearbox **G**eneration, starting with type 722.6 as generation **1**).
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] With 9 main components, it saves 2 components compared to the W5A 030.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] The most obvious flaw of the gearset concept is the second gear, which is clearly too short, but this affected all Mercedes-Benz transmissions, especially automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] The 7G-Tronic in 2003 was the first to remedy this situation.
[src:chrysler-300/5g-tronic] As shown in the assessment table below, another drawback of the gearset concept is the significant reduction in speed increase in 5th gear.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The World Forum for Harmonization of Vehicle Regulations define **AEBS** (also **automated emergency braking** in some jurisdictions).
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] UN ECE regulation 131 requires a system which can automatically detect a potential forward collision and activate the vehicle braking system to decelerate a vehicle with the purpose of avoiding or mitigating a collision.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] UN ECE regulation 152 says deceleration has to be at least 5 m/s².
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Once an impending collision is detected, these systems provide a warning to the driver.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] When the collision becomes imminent, they can take action autonomously without any driver input (by braking or steering or both).
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Collision avoidance by braking is appropriate at low vehicle speeds (e.g. below 50 km/h (31 mph)), while collision avoidance by steering may be more appropriate at higher vehicle speeds if lanes are clear.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Cars with collision avoidance may also be equipped with adaptive cruise control, using the same forward-looking sensors.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] AEB differs from forward collision warning: FCW alerts the driver with a warning but does not by itself brake the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Time-to-collision could be a way to choose which avoidance method (braking or steering) is most appropriate.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A collision avoidance system by steering is a new concept.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] It is considered by some research projects.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Collision avoidance system by steering has some limitations: over-dependence on lane markings, sensor limitations, and interaction between driver and system.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Early warning systems were attempted as early as the late 1950s.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] An example is Cadillac, which developed a prototype vehicle named the Cadillac Cyclone which used the new radar technology to detect objects in front of the car with the radar sensors mounted inside "nose cones".
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] It was deemed too costly to manufacture.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The first modern forward collision avoidance system was patented in 1990 by William L.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The second modern forward collision avoidance system was demonstrated in 1995 by a team of scientists and engineers at Hughes Research Laboratories (HRL) in Malibu, California.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The project was funded by Delco Electronics and was led by HRL physicist Ross D.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The technology was marketed as *Forewarn*.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The system was radar-based – a technology that was readily available at Hughes Electronics, but not commercially elsewhere.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A small custom fabricated radar antenna was developed specifically for this automotive application at 77 GHz.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The first production laser adaptive cruise control on a Toyota vehicle was introduced on the Celsior model (Japan only) in August 1997.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In 2008, AEB was introduced in the British market.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Between 2010 and 2014, Euro NCAP rewarded various constructors whose system had AEB features.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) studied whether to make frontal collision warning systems and lane departure warning systems mandatory.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In 2011, the European Commission investigated the stimulation of "collision mitigation by braking" systems.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Mandatory fitting (extra cost option) of Advanced Emergency Braking Systems in commercial vehicles was scheduled to be implemented on 1 November 2013 for new vehicle types and on 1 November 2015 for all new vehicles in the European Union.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] According to the "impact assessment", this could prevent around 5,000 fatalities and 50,000 serious injuries per year across the EU.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In March 2016, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) and the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety announced the manufacturers of 99% of U.S. automobiles had agreed to include automatic emergency braking systems as standard on virtually all new cars sold in the U.S. by 2022.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In Europe, there was a related agreement about an AEBS or AEB in 2012.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] United Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UNECE) has announced that this kind of system will become mandatory for new heavy vehicles starting in 2015.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] AEBS is regulated by UNECE regulation 131.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] NHTSA projected that the ensuing accelerated rollout of automatic emergency braking would prevent an estimated 28,000 collisions and 12,000 injuries.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In 2016, 40% of US car model have AEB as an option.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] As of January 2017, in the United Kingdom, an estimated 1,586,103 vehicles had AEB.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] This makes AEB available in 4.3% of the British vehicle fleet.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] As of 2021, Consumer Reports shows a rise in automakers making city-speed AEB standard.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In 2021, six automakers included AEB on all models, up from two in 2020, indicating increased customer demand for this safety feature.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Since 2015, the NHTSA has recommended AEB for vehicles.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] As of 2021, it is not mandatory in the US vehicles.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] However, in 2016, the NHTSA convinced automobile manufacturers to include AEB in 99% of new cars car sold in the US by 1 September 2022.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] On 9 June 2021, in Phoenix, USA, a heavy truck going too fast for traffic conditions crashed with seven other vehicles on a motorway, killing four people and hurting nine.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Two days later, US National Transportation Safety Board, prepare a nine-person team to investigate this crash, and to assess whether automatic emergency braking in the truck would have helped to mitigate or prevent the crash.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In 2019, 66% of autobrake systems evaluate by the IIHS in 2019 models earn the highest rating of superior for front crash prevention.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In 2017, AEB is one of the most popular forms of ADAS in Japan, in Japan more than 40% of newly manufactured vehicles equipped with some type of ADAS had AEB.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In 2018, 84.6% of cars had a kind of AEB in Japan, but the certification goal was not met by each of them.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] — autofile «Japan to make automatic-emergency braking mandatory» 18 December 2019.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] From the fiscal year 2021, in Japan, all new cars should have automatic braking systems to prevent accidents, including with a car or pedestrian but not with cyclists, at speeds defined by three international regulations.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In the European Union, advanced emergency-braking system is required by law on new vehicle models from May 2022, and all new vehicles sold by May 2024.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In India, autonomous emergency braking system (AEB) could become mandatory on new cars by 2022.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In the United States, automakers voluntary committed to releasing automatic emergency braking as a standard feature on all new cars and trucks starting in 2022, to provide AEB three years earlier than through a regulatory process.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] AEB is set to be mandatory in cars and light trucks by September 2029.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In Australia where AEB is not yet mandatory, the federal government has suggested in a Regulation Impact Statement (RIS) that car-to-car and pedestrian AEB should be standard on all new models launched from July 2022 and all new vehicles sold from July 2024 like in the European Union.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] AEB systems are required on all newly introduced vehicle models from March 2023, and all models on sale in Australia from March 2025.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] For HGVs and buses, new UNECE standards have been defined to improve AEB.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] From 2025, in the EU, those new standards will apply to new types of vehicle.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Those changes were raised after crash inquiries which found some lorry drivers regularly switch off their AEB systems to drive closer to the vehicle in front.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The regulation change will limit system deactivation to 15 minutes with automatic re-engagement after 15 minutes.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A 2012 study by the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety examined how particular features of crash-avoidance systems affected the number of claims under various forms of insurance coverage.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The findings indicate that two crash-avoidance features provide the biggest benefits: (a) *autonomous braking* that would brake on its own, if the driver does not, to avoid a forward collision, and (b) *adaptive headlights* that would shift the headlights in the direction the driver steers.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] They found lane departure systems to be not helpful, and perhaps harmful, at the circa 2012 stage of development.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A 2015 Insurance Institute for Highway Safety study found forward collision warning and automatic braking systems reduced rear collisions.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A 2015 study based on European and Australasian data suggests the AEB can decrease rear-end collisions by 38%.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In the 2016 Berlin truck attack, the vehicle used was brought to a stop by its automatic braking system.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Collision avoidance features are rapidly making their way into the new vehicle fleet.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In a study of police-reported crashes, automatic emergency braking was found to reduce the incidence of rear-end crashes by 39 percent.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A 2012 study suggests that if all cars feature the system, it will reduce accidents by up to 27 percent and save up to 8,000 lives per year on European roads.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A 2016 US study on trucks, considering 6,000 CAS activations from over 3 million miles and 110,000 hours driving performed with year 2013 technology, find that CAS activations were the result of lead vehicle actions, such as braking, turning, switching lanes, or merging.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In the UK and the US, third-party damages and costs have decreased by 10% and 40% according to some insurances.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In April 2019, IIHS/HLDI considered real-world benefits of crash avoidance technologies, based on rates of police-reported crashes and insurance claims.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The rear automatic braking is considered to have generated a 78% decrease in backing crashes (when combined with the rearview camera and parking sensor).
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] However, repair costs with this equipment are an average of US$109 higher due to the sensors being in areas prone to damage.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In Australia, AEB has been found to reduce police-reported crashes by 55 percent, rear-end crashes by 40 percent, and vehicle occupant trauma by 28 percent.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A 2020 Italian study suggests AEB reduces rear-end collision by 45% based on data from event data recorders in a sample of 1.5 million vehicles in 2017 and 1.8 million in 2018, for recent vehicles.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] It has been estimated that ALKS could help to avoid 47,000 serious accidents and save 3,900 lives over the first decade in the United Kingdom.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] A NTSB communication suggests that some vehicle collision avoidance assist systems are not able to detect damaged crash attenuators.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Therefore, the vehicle may drive into the crash attenuator.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The NTSB considers such a feature would be a must-have for safety with partially automated vehicles to detect potential hazards and warn of potential hazards to drivers.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Inclement weather such as heavy rain, snow, or fog may temporarily inhibit the effectiveness of the systems.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In Japan, there were 72 car-reported accidents in 2017, 101 in 2018, and 80 between January and September 2019 caused by drivers placing too much confidence in automatic brakes, with 18 of them resulting in injuries or death.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Unnecessary AEB might trigger in situations such as shadows on the road, cars parked or metal road signs on the side of the middle of a curve, steep driveways.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] AEB systems aim to detect possible collisions with the car in front.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] This is performed using sensors to detect and classify things in front of the vehicle, a system to interpret the data from the sensors, and a braking system which can work autonomously.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Some cars may implement lane departure warning systems.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Since 2004, Honda has developed a night vision system that highlights pedestrians in front of the vehicle by alerting the driver with an audible chime and visually displaying them via HUD.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Honda's system only works in temperatures below 30 degrees Celsius (86 Fahrenheit).
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] This system first appeared on the Honda Legend.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] To assist in pedestrian safety as well as driver safety, Volvo implemented a pedestrian airbag in the Volvo V40, introduced in 2012.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Many more manufacturers are developing Pedestrian crash avoidance mitigation (PCAM) systems.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] AEB with pedestrian detection was a feature to be included in the US National Highway Transportation Safety Authority's New Car Assessment Program, a safety scoring system for vehicles, but its inclusion was delayed in 2025 at the request of motordom.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] Since 2018, the ANCAP provides AEB rating and tests AEB features.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] The ANCAP report in its adult occupant protection section contains AEB rating taking into account AEB City from 10 to 50 km/h.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] In the US by 2017, 5% of cars were capable of reverse automatic braking.
[src:chrysler-300/active-braking] This feature allows autonomous braking of the vehicle while working in the reverse direction, to avoid a reverse collision.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The **Chrysler 300** is a full-size car produced by Chrysler under Stellantis North America and its predecessors.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The first generation (model years 2005–2010) was available as a four-door sedan and station wagon, in the second generation (model years 2011–2023) was available solely as a sedan.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The second generation 300 was marketed as the **Chrysler 300C** in the United Kingdom and Ireland and as the Lancia Thema in the remainder of Europe.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] When the company began operations in 1925, the Chrysler Six was entered as a roadster in the 1925 24 Hours of Le Mans where it finished the race.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In 1926, the Chrysler Imperial started the luxury and performance products tradition.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Starting in 1955, the Imperial became a separate luxury brand and offered the Imperial Newport along with the Imperial Crown.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The original Chrysler *FirePower* Hemi engine powered the Cunningham C-5R, a special racecar, and finished the 1952 Le Mans, 1953 Le Mans, and 1954 Le Mans endurance races, as well as the 1953 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 300 debuted as a concept at the 2003 New York International Auto Show with styling by Ralph Gilles, and production started in January 2004 for the 2005 model year.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The Chrysler 300 was designed as a modern interpretation of the 1955 Chrysler C-300 (and the letter series Chryslers that followed), featuring a large grille, long hood and low roofline that was prominent on those vehicles.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The styling retained many elements of the 1998 Chrysler Chronos concept car, such as chrome interior accents and tortoiseshell finishing on the steering wheel and shifter knob.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It was the last Chrysler vehicle designed under Tom Gale upon his retirement from DaimlerChrysler in December 2000.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It shares a nameplate with the 1957 300C letter series two-door hardtop and convertible.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The five-speed NAG1 W5A580 transmission, rear differential, driveshaft, ESP & ABS systems, steering system, the CAN Bus electrical architecture, and cabin electronics, including other electronic and engine modules, were derived from Mercedes-Benz components.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Further, switchgear such as the cruise control and turn signal combination stalk, seat controls, seat frames, HVAC system(s), and the wiring harness were utilized from Mercedes-Benz components.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Later model years also feature a Mercedes-Benz-derived laser key ignition system instead of the traditional metal key.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The AWD models also benefited from using Mercedes-Benz's 4MATIC system, including transfer case components.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The basic **300** includes 17-inch wheels, wheel covers, four-wheel disc brakes, a single disc CD player, an auxiliary input jack, a power driver seat, and a four-speed (42RLE) automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In Canada, it came standard with the **Touring** model's 3,518 cc (3.5 L; 214.7 cu in) V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The vehicle comes with standard rear-wheel drive and available all-wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The basic 300 model was renamed to **LX** for 2008 and remains the code name for the platform.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] This model was renamed **Touring Plus** for the 2009 and 2010 model years.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The **Limited** model included the Touring model's 3.5 L V6 engine, generating 250 hp (186 kW) and 250 lb⋅ft (339 N⋅m) and either a four- or five-speed transmission depending on the year and drive configuration.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Additional features included 18-inch chrome-clad aluminum road wheels and anti-roll bars.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Using the Multi-Displacement System (MDS), this engine can run on four cylinders when less power is needed to reduce total fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The USEPA-rated fuel consumption of the 300C is: 15 miles per US gallon (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) city, and 23 miles per US gallon (10 L/100 km; 28 mpg‑imp) highway.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] When all eight cylinders are needed, the 300C can produce 340 hp (254 kW) and 390 lb⋅ft (529 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It uses a five-speed automatic transmission and comes standard with 18-inch chrome-clad alloy wheels, Chrysler's *MyGIG Infotainment System* in 2008, as well as Sirius Satellite Radio and *Backseat Television* in 2008.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The Hemi cylinder heads necessitate a double rocker arm shaft configuration with a cam-in-block, overhead valve (OHV) pushrod design.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] There are two spark plugs per cylinder to promote efficient fuel/air mixture burn and reduce emissions.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The **SRT8** model was equipped with a 6.1 L Hemi engine producing 425 hp (317 kW; 431 PS) at 6,200 rpm and 420 lb⋅ft (569 N⋅m) of torque at 4,800 rpm.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The SRT8 can accelerate from 0–60 mph (97 km/h) in 4.9 seconds.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In 2006, Chrysler began producing a package group for the 300C model called "SRT Design”, which combined the 5.7L Hemi V8 engine with all the refinements and sports setup of the SRT 8.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] However, outside of North America, the SRT Design was only offered with the 3.0L V6 CRD engine.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In North America the last models of these to release were in 2009, production kept going globally until the face-lift in 2011.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] This model was predominantly used in the European market.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Chrysler marketed the 300C in Europe, Australia, South America, the Middle East, and Japan as both a four-door notchback sedan and a five-door station wagon.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The five-door station wagon was marketed as the **300C Touring** (not to be confused with the North American notchback sedan's "Touring" trim level), which shared its sheet metal aft of the C-pillar and wheel designs with the Dodge Magnum.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The base Chrysler 300 was not marketed in Europe.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] All cars came with the 300C body style/interior and either V6 diesel or V8 gasoline engines.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The economical V6 diesel, sourced from Mercedes-Benz, was optional in Europe.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Like the Magnum, an SRT8 variant of the 300C Touring with the 6.1 L Hemi engine was offered in Australia and Europe.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] All 300C Touring models, along with European 300C sedans and right-hand drive models, were assembled by Magna Steyr in Graz, Austria, beginning in June 2005.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Steyr insisted on upgrading suspension components to suit European tastes.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Dodge Charger/Magnum wheels with Chrysler center caps were used instead of the distinct wheels used on Canada-assembled models.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The five-door station wagon body style was discontinued after the first generation.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In Europe and Australia, the 300C was available with a Mercedes-Benz 3.0 L diesel V6 engine (internal code OM642) rated 218 PS (160 kW; 215 hp) at 3800 rpm and 376 lb⋅ft (510 N⋅m) of torque at 1600 rpm.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It can accelerate from 0–60 mph (97 km/h) in 7.9 seconds while the top speed remains the same as the gasoline V6 (140 mph (225 km/h)).
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 2008 UK models included the 300C SRT-Design model in sedan or Touring body, which included SRT 20-inch alloy wheels and wheel arch spats, chrome mesh grille, MyGIG satellite navigation, SRT8 steering wheel, SRT8 leather sports seats, and carbon fiber interior details.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] ASC created a convertible version of the Chrysler 300C, dubbed the ASC Helios 300, and unveiled it at the North American International Auto Show in early 2005.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Despite rumors, Chrysler confirmed that the vehicle would not be produced.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Chrysler Executive Series 300** was an extended wheelbase version shown at the 2006 New York Auto Show.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It added 6 inches (152 mm) to the rear passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The wheelbase was 126 in (3,200 mm) for this edition.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Chrysler Signature Executive Series 300** was a package offered from the factory for the touring V6 model after 2008.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It shared many features with the executive series, omitting the extra 6 inches and the rear DVD player in the passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It was offered for an additional CA$ 2,240 in Canada.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The Beijing Auto T8 was a Chinese limousine version of the Chrysler 300.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The T8 got a new Cadillac-style nose and a new rear end; however, the rest of the design remained unchanged from the standard Chrysler 300.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The only changes to the interior were a revised steering wheel with an updated logo.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Beijing Auto did not have the right to continue to use the platform(s) or engine(s) necessary to produce the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Therefore, the continuation of the T8's development and production prospects ended in 2009.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The Chrysler 300's driving characteristics were generally well-received.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The ride of the car was described as "steady, comfortable, and a study in control" Reviewers said the car drove "a lot like a Benz" due to the heavy use of German engineering and involvement of Mercedes-Benz in the development process during Chrysler and Daimler's partnership.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The car was also described as "impressively stable at high speed" by journalists at speeds even in excess of 150+ MPH on German autobahns, on par with other German sedans of the era.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Again, such attributes could be attributed to the car's German underpinnings.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In the UK, the BBC's *Top Gear* team described the 300C as "something different with a bit of kitsch gangster cool".
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] They praised the spacious and well-equipped interior, even calling it a "re-shelled German car with an American body," and the low price while criticizing the quality of certain materials, numb steering, and low engine torque of the V6 models.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The first generation model was popular with British buyers who regarded it as the "poor man's Bentley".
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In the US, the 300C enjoyed a wave of popularity in the mid-2000s, aided by celebrity owners (including US President Barack Obama,) and appearances in music videos.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In 2004, rapper Snoop Dogg famously called then-Chrysler CEO, Dieter Zetsche, asking for his own 300C; he later appeared in a commercial for the car alongside Lee Iacocca.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] 12 in a Complex.com article, "The 25 Most Iconic Hip-Hop Cars", due to its popularity in many hip-hop music videos following its introduction.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Chrysler 300 designer Ralph Gilles reflected on the vehicle's success in 2008, saying that the "300 turned out to be a bit of an icon for Chrysler".
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 300C was the 2005 *Motor Trend* Car of the Year.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It was on *Car and Driver's* Ten Best list for both 2005 and 2006.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] *Automobile Magazine* named it Automobile of the Year.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It also won the *North American Car of the Year* award.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It was voted Canadian Car of the Year by automobile journalists as the *Best New Luxury Car*.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Receiving numerous other recognitions during its debut year, it was promoted as being one of the most awarded new cars ever.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 300C was also included in the finalists for 2005 World Car of the Year, but final points total put it in fifth place equal to the BMW 1-series.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] A redesigned 300 was introduced in 2011 as a four-door sedan.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] However, the core platform of the car, now called the 'LD' while updated, was still closely related to the original 'LX' platform.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] While the suspension was revised, the front suspension is still derived from the design of the Mercedes-Benz S-Class (W220) and the 5-link rear design from the Mercedes-Benz E-Class (W211).
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Options included a dual-pane panoramic sunroof and 20-inch polished aluminum wheels.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 2011 model was offered in Touring, Limited, 300C, and 300C AWD trim levels.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Touring and Limited trims included the Pentastar V6, while the 300C line offered a standard 5.7 L Hemi.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] A new 300C Executive Series luxury trim level was introduced alongside a new 300S trim at the 2011 New York International Auto Show.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The sport-themed 300S featured black treatment for the grille and headlamps, 20-inch polished-face aluminum wheels with black painted pockets, 10-speaker *Beats by Dr.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Dre* sound system, and steering wheel mounted paddle shifters.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The Executive/Luxury Series was also sold in Europe, rebranded as the Lancia Thema from 2011 until 2014.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] For the 2021 model year, the 300C and Limited trim levels were dropped, leaving the Touring, Touring L, and 300S, which included the previous year's Red S Appearance Package as standard.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] An SRT version was unveiled at the 2011 New York International Auto Show, featuring the 6.4 L 392 Hemi V8 engine.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 6.4 L 392 Hemi engine is also used in other Chrysler Group SRT vehicles such as the Dodge Charger and Challenger.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] With 470 hp (350 kW), the new 300 SRT can go from 0 to 60 mph (97 km/h) in the low 4-second range.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In addition to the increase in power, the SRT receives specific exterior trim including a lower front fascia, large exhaust tips, body-color instead of chrome trim, and 20-inch (508 mm) aluminum wheels.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The car also gets a lowered, sportier suspension setup and a large Brembo brake package.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 300 SRT (or SRT8) was discontinued for the 2015 model year in the United States, but continued to be sold in Australia, New Zealand and the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In Australia, the 300 SRT Core (a base level trim offered in the Australian and New Zealand markets) was utilised by the New South Wales Police Force as a significant part of their Traffic and Highway Patrol fleet.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] These have since been withdrawn from service.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 300 SRT was sold in left and right-hand drive abroad.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] After a decade of falling sales in Australia, production of right-hand-drive versions ended in 2021.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The predecessors' 2.7 and 3.5 L engines were replaced with Chrysler's new 3.6 L Pentastar V6 engine producing 292 hp (218 kW) and 260 lb⋅ft (353 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The 5.7 L Hemi V8 engine remained available with 363 hp (271 kW).
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] A 3.0 L VM Motori V6 turbodiesel is also available in Europe, and Australia.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Beginning with the 2012 model year, all V6 models were equipped with the 8-speed 845RE Chrysler Torqueflite automatic transmission, licensed from ZF Friedrichshafen.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Interior changes included a revised instrument panel with localized "soft-touch" materials, 8.4-inch Uconnect Touch, a new steering wheel and center console, and standard leather seating on all trim levels.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Both seat-mounted and curtain-side airbags were standard.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In late 2014, a facelift version of the 300 was introduced.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] As part of the 2011 Chrysler 300 advertising campaign, three TV commercials were produced.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] "Homecoming" featured Detroit Lions defensive lineman Ndamukong Suh driving through his rainy hometown of Portland, Oregon, in his new 2011 Chrysler 300, retracing his humble beginnings.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] "Attitude" featured John Varvatos seeking inspiration at a record store in Brooklyn taking a record under his arm and into his Chrysler 300.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Dre driving through the streets of Los Angeles in a Beats by Dre equipped 2012 Chrysler 300.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The "See It Through"' TV commercial featured the Chrysler 300 and notable Detroit locals, including former Detroit Lion Ndamukong Suh and a poem written in 1917 by Edgar Guest titled "See It Through".
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] At the Detroit Motor Show in 2013, Chrysler presented a 300S paying homage to the 1964 Chrysler Turbine.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] It was finished in two-tone bronze and black, with an over-chrome grille and a 22-inch wheel design reminiscent of the turbine motif.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In March 2024, Stellantis issued a voluntary recall on Dodge Charger and Chrysler 300 cars, between model years 2018 to 2021, the recall affected more than 284,000 cars.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] The recall relates to the side curtain airbag inflators, that some of the modules could rupture and send Shrapnel pieces into the vehicle, injuring the occupants.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] In 2022, Stellantis confirmed that the Chrysler 300 sedan would be discontinued after the 2023 model year due to poor sales and due to the company's plans to focus its future on electric vehicles rather than fossil fuel-powered vehicles.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Stellantis would replace the Chrysler 300 with a Chrysler-badged all-electric vehicle previewed by the Chrysler Airflow EV concept.
[src:chrysler-300/chrysler-300] Production ended December 8, 2023, with the final vehicle being a Velvet Red 300C.
